title: For Sale:  1895 Winchester 30 Goverment 03. Capable of firing 30-06
postcontent: This great old rifle was built on May 4th 1911 by Winchester. There is some pitting in the nickel steel receiver, this is common in old 95's. The rust blued barrel retains most of the bluing, no rust, and has a great bore. This old repeater has the famous Climbing Lyman rear sight, probably from the factory, this was a common option on these long range repeaters. The rear dovetail has a filler plug that looks like it's always has been there. Teddy Roosevelt's favorite rifle was a 1895 Winchester he named Big Medicne. The 30-03 was the U.S. Military's official caliber for a very short time. A guy named Spitizer designed a pointed full metal jacket bullet to replace the big, round bullet designed for the 03 Springfield ergo the 30-06 we all know and love. Most of the 30-03's went to the Mexicans fighting their Revolution. (we had a bunch of surplus ammo). this rifle fires 30-06 ammo through it's shiny bore like a champ. I have had this fine piece of history a long time. The stock has some dents, it appears that it rode in a rifle rack a good bit. The wood has no cracks, it's a rock solid rifle. I can send a lot of photos. It even has some black ebony or buffalo horn in it's forearm. It is all original. I saw one like this in rough shape for sale with a price of $3000.00. I would feel guilty and sleep poorly if I received that much. I will take $1800 though, it is worth much more. If you have read this far thanks, text if you wish seven seven seven 9566 I appreciate your interest, Eric J. Eric Tinsley

postcontent:
Antique Colt Second Model Dragoon Revolver
 
Rare and Desirable Model of Colt’s Horse Pistol
 
Here we present an antique, much sought after Colt Second Model Dragoon Revolver. This pistol was designed for use by horse-mounted rifleman, and it is so much pistol that you will want a horse to carry it for you. This pistol weighs in at over 4 pounds.
 
The Second Model was first offered in 1850 and continued production through 1851, for a total of only 2,700, the rarest of Colt’s models of Dragoons. Colt’s Dragoons experienced some of the harshest conditions the mid-19th century had to offer, and it is amazing that any survived, especially in this condition.
 
This specimen is in fantastic condition, as cleaned. The one piece, walnut grips have been refinished and still preserve the inspector cartouche “WAT” for Capt. William Anderson Thornton. The frame also bears the “U.S.” under the “Colt’s Patent” marking. The cylinder shows the entirety of the Texas Ranger Indian Battle scene, with only small detail lost to age and cleaning. It is still quite clear. The action is excellent. All serial numbers match. This is a great addition for any collection.
 
Own the original! This is a legitimate antique and not a reproduction. Compare to other 2nd Model Dragoons available for up to $55,000 or more!
 
Barrel is 7.5 inches in length.
 
Caliber: .44 percussion
 
Bore is in very good condition and the firearm is in working order.
 
Overall condition as seen in photos.
 
Here is a fantastic 2nd Model Dragoon to be the crown jewel of your collection.
